(preamble
  :dialect "sakura"
  :audience "engineer"
  :training-eligible #f
  :confidentiality "internal"
  :prose "Canonical engineering doc #8 of the sealed Sakura Scheme 1.0 doc-set. Pairs with LACUNA-INTEGRATION-1.0.ENG.md (the upstream wire-call manual this telemetry observes), LOAM-1.0.ENG.md (substrate where telemetry lands), and the sealed doc-set. Audience: SRE; any engineer adding instrumentation to a new capability; any auditor confirming cost ledger + audit chain are honest; any operator who asks 'is Lacuna healthy?' and expects a real answer. Voice: HelloSurface gold standard — dry, structured, data-rich, file:line-anchored. Instrumentation is the surface where honesty matters most: if telemetry lies, every downstream decision is wrong. This document names every signal recorded, every place it lands, every place it is read, and — as importantly — every signal deliberately NOT recorded. Author: Alfred Robins / Claude Code (PM lane) 2026-06-30. Covers-through 2026-07-11 (drift pass vs HEAD d4f5a8a4; Meridian project docs folded 2026-07-11).")

(chapter :number 1
         :title "§0 — Telemetry philosophy (five rules, three observers, three signal kinds)"
         :section "0"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§0"))
         :prose "Five non-negotiable rules. Each is a direct consequence of an architect commitment to the operators paying for the product (CLAUDE.md 'Honest nulls, no fluent-wrong' + 2026-06-27 trust verbatim). (1) Honest-null applies to metrics. A counter that didn't fire is 0, not 'unavailable.' A counter the host can't reach is 'unavailable', not 0. Never blur them. (2) No fabricated numbers. If a number is computed, it cites its inputs. If sampled, it carries its sample window. If estimated, the word 'estimated' appears in the column header (cost_ledger.py:436 est = 0.05 if ... is an estimate and surfaces as estimated_cost_usd). (3) Privacy-first. Operator PII never lands in a telemetry row. Audit pipe (preamble.py:257-278 audit_line) carries trace_id only — verbatim comment from Zain (security): 'this is what hits the log file. trace_id only — NEVER the full preamble (no PII bleed).' (4) Vendor names land in ledger rows; never in operator-facing dashboards. Per cost_ledger.py:148-160 — ledger stores literal upstream tags (anthropic-realtime, gemini-batch) for SRE drill-down; rollup_for_tier translates them into capability names (reasoner-realtime, workhorse-batch) before any operator-facing payload renders them. Leak-scan exclude path knows the difference (cost_ledger.py:162-165). (5) Recursive observability. Loam writes its own state into Loam. Substrate IS its own observability surface. No special admin backdoor. SRE asking 'why did this read fail?' uses the same Shell, cap-token, audit log discipline as any cart (LOAM §21.1).

Three observers. Telemetry serves three distinct readers; each gets a different projection of the same signal stream — never a separate stream: SRE / Lacuna Engineering sees raw per-vendor tags, raw per-shard latency, raw error class, raw upstream URL at /systems/monitoring + /api/admin/cost/* + /api/sre/*. Sakura (on-device savant + L1) sees capability-tagged rollups, anomaly summaries, narration hooks; vendor names FIREWALLED out; surface = cart-status thread bus events + Loam SYSTEM/sakura-recs. Operator sees cart-level performance receipts, per-tier budget status, per-vendor service health (UP/DEGRADED/DOWN with vendor identity scrubbed to 'marketplace' or 'model service'); surface = Automations dossier + activity sheet + operator settings. Every signal in this document carries a 'who reads it' annotation. Routing the same signal three ways without leaking SRE-level detail to operator (or operator PII into SRE pipe) is the discipline.

Three signal kinds. (1) Events. A cart fires; a verb completes; an escalation surfaces. Append-only, sequence-numbered, timestamped. cartBus.js is client-side event spine; preamble.audit_line is server-side event spine. Both fan into Loam SYSTEM plane. (2) Counters. Per-tier daily-cap budget; hard-cap breach counter; rolling-24h cost. Lock-protected, in-process; mirrored into Loam every wave. cost_ledger.py:191-203 carries canonical counter set. (3) Health probes. A vendor's is_configured() returns False — wire-call surface reports DEGRADED. A shard's replication lag exceeds threshold — substrate reports DEGRADED-READ. Probes are pull-based (SRE asks); event + counter streams are push-based (system tells SRE).")

(chapter :number 2
         :title "§1 — Cart lifecycle events (cartBus taxonomy + guarantees + bridge + gate + server mirror)"
         :section "1"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§1"))
         :prose "The cartBus event taxonomy (curator-web/src/scheme/cartBus.js:28-56). Every cart run emits a typed event stream. Same bus drives three consumers (cartBus.js:1-22): live D3 visualisation (CartFlowChart subscribes, lights nodes); recorder (writes events to log buffer + exports JSON); replayer (drives fresh cart, intercepts act calls, returns response from log so same sequence emerges). Replay is the load-bearing feature — operator's prod log replays identically on the SRE laptop; requires every event to carry a sequence number and monotonic timestamp.

Event set. CART_START ('cart-start') fired when cartHost.js begins a cart run; payload {cartId, runId, slug, startedAt}. CART_END ('cart-end') fired when 'done' returned OR cart halted; {cartId, runId, reason, finishedAt}. STATE_ENTER ('state-enter') fired when driver enters a state; {state, ctxKeys} (ctx VALUES NOT logged). STATE_EXIT ('state-exit') fired when driver exits a state; {state, descriptor}. ACT_REQUEST ('act-request') fired when cart calls (act 'verb args ...); {verb, argsHash, on-result} (args HASHED, not logged verbatim). ACT_RESPONSE ('act-response') fired when driver receives verb result; {verb, argsHash, ok, duration_ms}. ACT_PROGRESS ('act-progress') for long-running act; {verb, p} where p in [0,1]. ESCALATE fired when state fn returns (escalate 'kind detail); {kind, detailHash}. WAIT fired when state fn returns (wait 'event); {event}. AFTER fired when state fn returns (after seconds 'state ...); {seconds, state}. ERROR fired on malformed descriptor / invariant violation; {message, state, cartSlug}. INTERRUPTED fired on live-voice mid-speech interruption; {reason, state}. PRIMITIVE_CRASH fired when primitive throws inside state fn; {cartSlug, state, primitive, message, stack, timestamp, ctxKeys}.

Per cartBus.js:47-55: PRIMITIVE_CRASH payload names ctx slots present at crash time but never their values — 'a crash should not leak operator data into the log bus.' Canonical example of the §0.1 privacy rule applied at event-payload boundary.

Sequence + timestamp guarantees. Every event carries: seq (monotonically increasing per CartBus instance); t (monotonic timestamp ms since CartBus construction); dt_ms (delta from previous event). Per cartBus.js:96-103 — nowMs() captured exactly once per emit; same value reused for t, dt_ms, and startedAt seed so hot cart runs don't burn CPU on three monotonic-clock reads per event.

CartBus → ChipSink bridge. Per cartBus.js:23-26 — every emitted bus event is also converted to chip.v1 envelope and appended to chipSink. This is how the chip economy gets populated: operators (and Sakura) drag log entries straight into automations without any marshaling step. Field contract locked at src/lib/chipEvent.md.

Multi-step gate. Per cartBus.js:65-78 — isMultiStep flag (default true) filters out one-shot tool calls from AutomationPulseButton + ActivitySheet surfaces. Single tool calls (one-shot API hits) set false and are filtered out. Defaulting true preserves back-compat for existing callers that haven't been annotated yet.

Server-side mirror. Client-side cartBus is mirrored server-side via audit pipe (preamble.audit_line, §8). Every backing handler emits one audit line per dispatch: _audit(preamble, verb, 'received', ...) on entry; _audit(preamble, verb, 'ok', ...) on success; _audit(preamble, verb, 'reject', ...) on shape/auth rejection; _audit(preamble, verb, 'error', ...) on exception; _audit(preamble, verb, 'ok-degraded', ...) on honest-null. Visible at routes/verb_backings.py:153-156 (_audit helper) and in every route handler in the file.")

(chapter :number 3
         :title "§2 — Cost ledger (per-vendor); row schema; rollup translation; hard caps; ring buffer; batch/cache shaping"
         :section "2"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§2"))
         :prose "Cost ledger module: curator-api/curator_api/llm_router/cost_ledger.py (787 lines as of 2026-07-03; 732 at 2026-06-30 draft). Replaces what Vertex AI's 'consolidated invoice' would have provided. Per docstring (:1-7): 'Matches Vertex's consolidated invoice benefit on the direct-vendor paths. Tally every LLM wire-call into a single append-only ledger so operators (and SRE) get one truthful surface for spend.' Two public surfaces (:21-23): record_call(call) — write, fast hot-path; summarize(*, bucket, since, until, operator_id, tier) — read, admin API + widget.

Cost row schema (cost_ledger.py:25-41, one CBOR-encoded row per call). {tier_id: 'anthropic-realtime' | 'anthropic-batch' | ...; verb: 'model/reasoner' | 'model/opus' | ...; model: 'claude-sonnet-4-5-20251022' | ...; input_tokens: int; output_tokens: int; cache_creation: int; cache_read: int; batch_discount: bool; cost_usd: float; trace_id: str (cart dispatch propagation); operator_id: str; tier: str (free | imagine | dream | magic); ts_unix: float (auto-stamped if missing)}. Vendor-name lock special case (cost_ledger.py:7-15): tier_id IS the literal upstream tag for accounting reasons. Ledger row payload contains vendor identifiers. Ledger is read by SRE (engineering surface) and NEVER shown verbatim on operator marketplace UI. Aggregate API + dashboard widget collapses upstream tags into capability-named rollups before serving operator-facing payloads.

Tier → rollup translation (cost_ledger.py:148-160). anthropic-realtime → reasoner-realtime (batch=False); anthropic-batch → reasoner-batch (batch=True); anthropic-opus → deep-reasoner-realtime (batch=False); gemini-realtime → workhorse-realtime (batch=False); gemini-batch → workhorse-batch (batch=True); gemini-cache → cache (batch=False). rollup_for_tier(tier_id) is public API (:172-179). Unknown tier_ids fall through as 'unknown' rather than leaking raw upstream string. This is the §0.1 rule #4 enforcement point.

Loam plane: system/cost-ledger (cost_ledger.py:42-48). Plane: system/cost-ledger (append-only). Key: cost-ledger/<day-bucket>/<trace_id>. Encoding: CBOR. Subscription pattern per [[loam-impl-w9]]. Day-bucketing makes plane partitionable for archival; trace_id suffix means same trace = same key = idempotent re-write. Loam writes can be disabled in dev via CURATOR_COST_LEDGER_WRITE=off (:67); ring buffer still works.

Hard caps (cost_ledger.py:70-82). HARD_CAP_USD_PER_TIER = {free: 0.10, imagine: 1.00, dream: 10.00, magic: 100.00, default: 0.10}. Caps scale with pricing ladder ($0.10 / $1 / $10 / $100 per day). 'default' covers anonymous / no-tier ledger rows. Override hierarchy (:84-114): (1) CURATOR_COST_HARD_CAP_OVERRIDE_USD env (testing / emergency lockdown — applies to ALL tiers). (2) Per-operator Loam override at system/cost-caps/<operator_id> (resolved by cap_for_operator). (3) Per-tier value from HARD_CAP_USD_PER_TIER. (4) Legacy CURATOR_COST_HARD_CAP_USD env (back-compat). (5) Default slot ($0.10). Request that would breach → cost-cap-exceeded (breach counter hard_cap_breaches increments — SRE alert).

In-process ring buffer (cost_ledger.py:184-203). _RING_MAX = 4096; _RING: deque = deque(maxlen=_RING_MAX); _RING_LOCK = threading.Lock(). _COUNTERS = {total_calls, total_input_tokens, total_output_tokens, total_cache_creation_tokens, total_cache_read_tokens, total_cost_usd_micros (int micros to avoid float drift), hard_cap_breaches, rolling_24h_cost_usd_micros, loam_write_failures}. Ring buffer is hot-read cache so summarize() serves fast without Loam round-trip; Loam is source-of-truth (append-only). Float-drift discipline: cost stored as integer micros (cost_usd × 1_000_000) to avoid float accumulation error (:198, :211-227). Wave 7B discipline — earlier audits caught 0.00001-USD/call drift on summarize after ~10^4 rows that compounded to visible mis-reporting.

Admin read surface (per WAVE-7B:46-57). Two admin-only HTTP routes (404 to non-admin per existing admin discipline): GET /api/admin/cost/summary?bucket=<day|week|month>&operator=<id>&tier=<slug>; GET /api/admin/cost/dashboard-widget. Both serve through cost_ledger.summarize() / dashboard_widget_payload(). Dashboard-widget endpoint returns pre-shaped payload for SRE monitoring page.

Batch + cache cost shaping (per WAVE-7B:10-17). Anthropic: realtime $X, batch 0.5 × $X, cache not yet enabled. Gemini: realtime $Y, batch 0.5 × $Y, cache 0.25 × $Y on cached read after TTL. Cost ledger records actual paid amount per-call; rollup preserves batch-vs-realtime distinction so SRE can confirm batch tier delivers promised discount.")

(chapter :number 4
         :title "§3 — Per-operator usage tracking (token ledger, event taxonomy, cap overrides, Magic-default, Cortex write budget)"
         :section "3"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§3"))
         :prose "Token ledger (operator-facing). Source: PRICING-TOKEN-DESIGN-2026-06-18.md. Each operator carries a token budget that drips daily up to a per-tier cap. Cart cost is HMAC-signed at build time (scripts/build_cart_index.mjs:73-99, curator-api/curator_api/signing.py); dispatcher verifies on every cart load and rejects tampered costs.

Token event taxonomy (per MONITORING-SPEC.md:13-27). Every change to operator's token balance emits structured event: token.drip {operator_id, tier, tokens_added, new_balance, cap_hit: bool, ts}; token.spend {operator_id, tier, tokens_deducted, verb, cart_slug, new_balance, ts}; token.gift {operator_id, tier, tokens_added, reason (compassion | sla_credit | admin), new_balance, ts}; token.cap_hit {operator_id, tier, current_balance, cap_value, ts}; token.burst_reject {operator_id, tier, tokens_attempted, burst_limit, retry_after_ts, ts}; token.hmac_mismatch {operator_id, cart_slug, claimed_cost, recalculated_cost, ts}. Drip cadence monitoring (MONITORING-SPEC.md:25): histogram of drip intervals per operator per tier. Alert if any operator's drip skips more than two consecutive expected windows.

Per-operator cost cap override (cost_ledger.py:262-296, :297-318). cap_for_operator(operator_id, tier) resolves to per-operator override stored in Loam at system/cost-caps/<operator_id>, falling back to tier default. Override surface exists so SRE can grant Magic-tier-equivalent cap to Free user testing feature; pin runaway operator below Free cap as incident response; lift enterprise operator above Magic default for approved tier. Each override write to Loam is an audited event with SRE operator's identity in audit row.

Magic-default override (2026-06-23). Per CLAUDE.md 'Tier override — 2026-06-23' — every account treats as magic for now (curator-web/src/lib/operatorTier.js:getOperatorTier()). Token model, HMAC-signed cart costs, and backend daily-drip caps remain in place; they just never gate because Magic carries them all. Telemetry still fires. Cap-hit counters still bump. Honest visibility into what WOULD be gated if payment were on. When payment lands and flag flips, metric stream is already in production.

Cortex write budget per operator (curator-api/curator_api/cortex/write_budget.py). Independent of LLM cost cap — each operator has daily Cortex write cap (memo creation rate-limit). Visible at verb_backings.py:234-247 in cortex/remember handler. Was added as X9 / Cortex audit 2026-06-24 fix (:228-233): HTTP /api/cortex/write route gated, Scheme-verb path did not; cart-dispatch loop could drip past daily cap indefinitely via repeated (cortex/remember ...) calls. Now both paths converge on write_budget.check_and_bump.")

(chapter :number 5
         :title "§4 — Wire-call observability (counters, latency capture + LatencyRing, rate-limit envelope, /api/healthz/deep, voice/transcribe)"
         :section "4"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§4"))
         :prose "Per-wire-call counters. Each wire-call module reports outcome through audit pipe (§8). Aggregations: rate_limit_hits (429 from upstream) per-vendor per-day; quota_exhausted (daily quota burned) per-vendor per-day; auth_failures (401 → service-not-yet-wired) per-operator per-vendor; latency_p50_ms / p95 / p99 (wire-call duration) per-vendor per-hour; upstream_error_rate (5xx/502/504 over total) per-vendor per-hour; cost-cap-exceeded events (cost ledger rejection) per-operator per-day.

Latency capture pattern. Every route handler measures end-to-end duration. Conceptual pattern from verb_backings.py:170+: parse request, _audit received (t0), await backing (t1-t0 = backing duration), except _audit error with error_class, _audit ok with chars/etc (t2). Duration between received and ok is operator-perceived latency; SRE aggregates per-vendor; alerts fire when p95 exceeds threshold per MONITORING-SPEC.md.

Per-verb latency write path (wired 2026-07). Percentile metric names (latency-p50/p90/p95/p99-by-verb) were reserved in metric allow-list long before anything wrote them — outside Stores SLO surface (stores/slo.py), no code populated them. sre/latency_ring.py closes that gap. LatencyRing class (:64) is in-process, per-verb ring of most recent samples (MAX_SAMPLES_PER_VERB, deque so memory is bounded and percentile sort stays cheap). Wiring at HEAD: WRITE — routes/verb_backings.py:112 imports record_verb_latency and records duration_ms for every backing call that reaches t_ok. DRAIN — sre/timeseries.py:714 calls default_latency_ring().drain_percentiles(now=...) once per metric tick; draining clears the ring so each tick's percentiles cover only that window's samples. SNAPSHOT — sre/routes.py:675 calls snapshot_percentiles() for live SRE dashboard read (non-destructive — does not clear ring). EMPTY WINDOW IS HONEST-NULL — a tick with no samples for a verb returns no percentile rows; dashboard renders 'no data', not fabricated zero (sre/latency_ring.py:26-28). §0.1 rule #1 applied at percentile boundary. _percentile (sre/latency_ring.py:51) is nearest-rank and mirrors stores/slo.py:_percentile so the two latency surfaces agree on percentile definition. ML feature extractor (sre/ml/features.py:44) reads same snapshot_percentiles output, so anomaly model and dashboard see identical numbers.

Rate-limit envelope. Per LACUNA-INTEGRATION §4.3 and meta/dispatcher.py:73-76 — every rate-limited response carries {ok: False, error: 'rate-limited', reason: '<vendor>-rate-limit', retry_after_s: <float>}. SRE dashboard reads <vendor> field of the reason; operator-facing surface translates to 'the marketplace is busy.'

Probe surface (/api/healthz/deep). Source: curator-api/curator_api/_healthz_deep.py. What the deep healthcheck actually checks today (verified against _healthz_deep.py:238 run_deep_health at HEAD d4f5a8a4): deep probe runs four subchecks and returns {db, vendor, disk, memory} plus aggregate status code (:247). Host-liveness probe, not per-vendor configuration matrix. db (_check_db(db_path) at :69) — Cortex/listings SQLite reachable + writable. vendor (_check_vendor() at :105) — ONE egress probe (HTTP GET to httpbin.org/get, 2s timeout). Confirms box can reach public internet at all; does NOT probe any specific upstream (:12, :36). Single vendor egress probe is deliberately a 'dummy egress' canary (httpbin.org) — chosen so check names no real upstream and leaks no vendor identity into health surface. disk (_check_disk() at :130) — free-space headroom. memory (_check_memory() at :180) — available-memory headroom. Per-vendor matrix is separate, not-yet-unified surface. Each wire-call module does expose is_configured() boolean (batch_anthropic.py, batch_gemini.py, firecrawl/client.py:13-29 for keyless honest-null), and routing manifest probe (routing/l1_manifest.py, §4.5) reports per-capability readiness. But those are not aggregated into /api/healthz/deep today. Future per-vendor configured/last-success/last-rate-limit matrix — the shape below — is target, capability-tagged so no vendor string surfaces: rows per capability like model/reasoner (yes, 2min ago, 18min ago), model/workhorse (yes, 4min ago, none today), web/scrape (yes, in flight, none), etsy/* per-operator (yes for X, —, —).

On-device voice/transcribe observability (§4.5). Vendor-naming note: per CLAUDE.md firewall, this telemetry doc names capability verb voice/transcribe, never the model. Model identifier lives only in INTEGRATION wire-call manual (§2.13). Everything below is model-agnostic on purpose: same counters serve whichever backend (on-device or cloud fallback) actually served the request. Why this verb differs from every other in §4: every other row observes a network round-trip; voice/transcribe's primary path is on-device (§2.13 INTEGRATION) — audio never leaves phone/host, so no upstream latency to capture, no rate-limit envelope to read. Telemetry surface splits by backend: on-device — backend label 'local', latency captured is model inference wall-time (local), rate-limit envelope n/a, privacy note 'audio stays on device', configured probe l1_manifest.py:132 _check_voice_transcribe (imports nemo.collections.asr at :135); cloud fallback (FALLBACK_STT=google) — backend label 'fallback-cloud', latency captured is network round-trip (as §4.2), rate-limit envelope as §4.3, privacy note 'audio leaves device — MUST be surfaced in consent/audit trail', configured probe vendor is_configured(). Health/readiness: deep-healthcheck matrix (§4.4) gains voice-transcribe row driven by L1 manifest probe (routing/l1_manifest.py:60, :132, :174). Probe reports capability key, not model — so SRE reading /api/healthz/deep sees voice-transcribe: ready|degraded, never vendor string. Cost: on-device path has ZERO per-call cost — does not appear in per-vendor cost ledger (§2), because no vendor invoice. Cloud fallback (when explicitly enabled) bills through normal §2.1 cost-row path under its capability tier. Telemetry consequence of L0-STT lock: moving STT on-device removes recurring line item from ledger entirely. Privacy signal is load-bearing: because default path keeps audio on-device, any switch to cloud fallback is privacy-material event and MUST be observable — audit trail (§1.5) records backend=fallback-cloud so CIPA/BIPA review can prove exactly which transcriptions left device. Silent fallback would be compliance defect, not merely telemetry gap.")

(chapter :number 6
         :title "§5 — Cortex write events (memory module, memo lifecycle, write-budget signal, what is NOT logged)"
         :section "5"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§5"))
         :prose "Cortex memory module. Source: curator-api/curator_api/cortex/memory.py. Every memo creation, memo recall, memo expunge fires through CortexStore. Store is local SQLite-backed (per Cortex shell chain). Each operation is audited.

Memo lifecycle events. Create → verb cortex/remember → audit row verb_backings.py:262 _audit(preamble, 'cortex/remember', 'ok', {memo_id: memo_id}). Recall → verb cortex/recall → verb_backings.py:197 _audit(preamble, 'cortex/recall', 'ok', {hit_count: len(hits)}). Forget → cortex/forget → verb_backings.py:2154+. Calendar fetch → cortex/calendar → :2106+. Cosine top-k → cortex/cosine-topk → :2206+.

Write-budget signal. Per §3.5 — cortex/remember budget-exceeded events audited explicitly as 'refused' outcomes (verb_backings.py:237-246). SRE reads these to identify operators whose carts are looping or mis-configured.

What is NOT logged in Cortex events. Memo body content — audit row carries memo_id and caller's trace_id; body is in Cortex (encrypted at rest); does not appear in any log line. Recall query text — cortex/recall may carry a topic filter; filter string IS logged ONLY when it appears in args; SRE policy is to scrub it from any cross-operator analytics surface (LIVING:RESEARCH — confirm topic-filter scrubbing is enforced in any analytics pipeline that reads audit log). Hit memo IDs (beyond count) — cortex/recall audit logs hit_count, not IDs of hits. Operator's recall pattern is operator's pattern.")

(chapter :number 7
         :title "§6 — Loam plane queries (five planes, SYSTEM plane row table, query surface, COHORT K-floor, PUBLIC opt-in)"
         :section "6"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§6"))
         :prose "Per LOAM §1 — Loam is partitioned into planes. Each plane has its own consistency, retention, and access contract. Telemetry queries land on specific planes.

Five planes (per LOAM §1.1 + §1.4). TENANT — single operator; read/write by that operator's carts; per-operator cart performance receipts. COHORT — per-cohort aggregate (K-floor-gated); K-anonymous aggregate read-only for non-cohort-members; Sakura recommendation cohort fitness. WORLD — public knowledge (Cortex Knowledge Loop); append-only, audit-trail-mandatory; cohort outcomes opt-in publishable to PUBLIC. SYSTEM — internal (audit, reconciliation, SRE events); service writes / SRE reads; every telemetry channel listed in this document. PUBLIC — OPT-IN cohort outcomes promoted from COHORT; cohort-cohort sign-off; anonymous trend publications.

SYSTEM plane row table (per LOAM §21.1). SYSTEM/otel — OpenTelemetry spans per op. SYSTEM/metrics — Prometheus per-shard metrics (latency, throughput, error rate, replication lag, projection freshness). SYSTEM/slo — per-tenant SLO dashboards (p50/p95/p99 per tenant). SYSTEM/sakura-recs — Sakura's recommendation outcomes (accepted / succeeded / reverse-suggested). SYSTEM/self — Loam writing its own operational state into Loam. SYSTEM/cohort-outcomes — per-cohort outcomes (K-floor-gated; opt-in publishable to PUBLIC). SYSTEM/pattern-proposals — pattern-mining signal (clusters in audit log suggesting new cart candidates per §16.3.9). SYSTEM/cost-ledger — per-vendor cost ledger (§2.4 above). SYSTEM/audit — per-operator audit spine (§8 below).

Query surface. Telemetry queries use Loam Shell + cap-token discipline (per LOAM §14). SRE asking 'what was p95 latency for Anthropic batch submits on Tuesday?' writes a Loam read query against SYSTEM/metrics with SYSTEM-plane cap-token. Query is itself audited (SYSTEM/audit). This is the recursive observability rule (§0.1 #5) in operation: the act of observing telemetry IS itself telemetry.

COHORT plane K-floor. Per LOAM §13 — cohort plane enforces K-anonymity floor (default K=5). Cohort query that would return data from fewer than K operators is refused. Privacy floor on cross-operator aggregate signals. SRE dashboard's per-vendor latency aggregates are NOT subject to K-floor (vendor latency is not operator data); operator cohort outcomes ARE.

PUBLIC plane opt-in. Per LOAM §6.7 and §21.1 — SYSTEM/cohort-outcomes can be opt-in published to PUBLIC for Cortex Knowledge Loop. Publish step requires cohort cohort-member sign-off and strips any metadata that could re-identify cohort. This is how the system gets smarter without ever betraying the operator (per CLAUDE.md 2026-06-27 trust verbatim).")

(chapter :number 8
         :title "§7 — SRE dashboards at /systems/monitoring (web surface, charts, read paths, chat, bash-recovery)"
         :section "7"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§7"))
         :prose "SRE web surface. Source: curator-web/public/systems/monitoring/ (source folder), curator-web/dist/systems/monitoring/ (built artifact). Per dist evidence (curator-web/dist/systems/monitoring/app.js:200,229) SRE dashboard is served at /systems/monitoring/ with Google SSO auth gate (/api/sre/auth/google/start?back=...). Modules: /systems/monitoring/ (root dashboard); /systems/monitoring/#loam (Loam health per-shard, per-plane); /systems/monitoring/chat/ (SRE chat with provenance + identity); /systems/monitoring/charts/ (D3 chart components).

Per LOAM §41 ('SRE monitoring product' chapter added 2026-06-27 per AUDIT-LIES Priya I-2): 'Earlier drafts of this doc never named the SRE monitoring product even though ~6000 LoC of code under curator-api/curator_api/sre/ + curator-web/public/systems/monitoring/ ships it.'

Chart surface. D3 chart modules under /systems/monitoring/charts/ (chart-line.js etc.) read from admin cost endpoints (/api/admin/cost/summary, /api/admin/cost/dashboard-widget) and from Loam SYSTEM-plane reads via SRE backend API.

Dashboard read paths. Per-vendor cost (24h) — reads from cost_ledger._RING via dashboard_widget_payload(); hot ring buffer read; ~ms latency. Per-tier daily-cap burn — cost_ledger.summarize(bucket='day', tier=...); ring buffer + recent Loam window. Cart fire rate — SYSTEM/audit aggregated by verb per minute; Loam range read. Wire-call latency p95 — SYSTEM/metrics per-vendor histogram; Loam projection read. Shard health — SYSTEM/self per-shard freshness; recursive Loam read. Replication lag — SYSTEM/self per-shard; recursive. Anthropic batch queue depth — cost_ledger + per-call batch_id records; hybrid. Operator cost-cap breaches — _COUNTERS['hard_cap_breaches'] + SYSTEM/audit; counter + audit cross-ref.

Chat-with-context surface. SRE chat (/systems/monitoring/chat/) carries identity + crypto (/systems/monitoring/chat/identity.js, chat/crypto.js) so SRE queries against substrate are signed and audited. Recursive-observability rule again: SRE-on-SRE conversation is itself an audited substrate event.

Bash-recovery last-resort. Per LOAM §21.2.3 — loam-health.sh is last-resort observability when dashboards themselves are degraded. Single POSIX-tools + sqlite3 script; output is parseable, exit code is meaningful. SRE on-call uses it when web dashboards are down. Confirmed at HEAD d4f5a8a4: script lives at tools/loam-health.sh, which matches operational-scripts convention (a human runs it to operate the system → tools/, not scripts/).")

(chapter :number 9
         :title "§8 — Audit log spine (audit_line contract, field discipline, destination, propagation, retention)"
         :section "8"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§8"))
         :prose "audit_line contract (curator-api/curator_api/preamble.py:257-278). def audit_line(preamble: Preamble, verb: str, outcome: str, extra: Optional[Mapping[str, Any]] = None) -> str: renders THE ONE-LINE structured audit string for a backing call. Zain: 'this is what hits the log file. trace_id only — NEVER the full preamble (no PII bleed). The handler emits this on every accepted + rejected dispatch.' Line dict: {ts: preamble.audit.ts_iso, verb, trace_id: preamble.audit.trace_id, parent_trace_id: preamble.audit.parent_trace_id, tier: preamble.sakura.tier, model_route: preamble.sakura.model_route, cart_slug: preamble.doing.cart_slug, turn_phase: preamble.doing.turn_phase, outcome}. If extra, updates line with {k:v for k,v in extra.items() if k not in line}. Returns json.dumps(line, separators=(',', ':'), sort_keys=True).

Audit row field discipline. ts — ISO-8601 timestamp from preamble; NOT server-side wall clock (from cart's preamble so it ties to cart's view of 'now'). verb — capability verb name (etsy/listings); NOT a vendor name. trace_id — opaque tracing identifier; NOT user-meaningful ID. parent_trace_id — trace propagation for multi-call carts; NOT operator identity. tier — free/imagine/dream/magic; NOT the literal model name. model_route — capability route (fast/reasoner/deep-reasoner); NOT vendor. cart_slug — cart identifier; NOT cart contents. turn_phase — phase of cart's conversation turn; NOT message content. outcome — received/ok/reject/error/ok-degraded/refused; NOT a backtrace. Extra field carries operation-specific data — never operator PII. Pattern enforced per-handler (see verb_backings.py:175-198 for cortex/recall as canonical example).

Audit row destination. Per _audit helper at verb_backings.py:153-156: log = logging.getLogger('curator_api.verb_backings'); def _audit(preamble, verb, outcome, extra=None) → emit ONE audit line per backing call, trace_id only, no PII. Log line lands in application logger; log shipper writes into Loam SYSTEM/audit for retention and into SRE log analysis pipeline. Per LOAM §21 — audit log spine is itself auditable; SYSTEM/audit can be queried for 'every operation by trace_id X' with cap-token discipline.

Audit propagation across multi-call carts. parent_trace_id is propagation field. Cart that fires (act 'cortex/recall ...) then (act 'model/workhorse ...) then (act 'cortex/remember ...) produces three audit rows; each shares same cart_slug but distinct trace_ids, and second + third carry first's trace as parent_trace_id. This is how SRE reconstructs cart's narrative when investigating incident.

Audit row retention. Per LOAM §9 — SYSTEM-plane retention is policy-driven; audit spine retention is mandatory for compliance window operator's tier commits to. Default: 90 days hot, then cold-archive. LIVING:RESEARCH — document per-tier audit retention promise + cold-archive surface.")

(chapter :number 10
         :title "§9 — What is NOT measured + why (privacy floor, vendor-shaping floor, signal-not-noise floor, sampling decision)"
         :section "9"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§9"))
         :prose "The privacy floor. Following are NOT recorded under any circumstances. Memo body content (cortex/remember text) — operator's data; lives encrypted in Cortex; audit logs memo_id only. Cart state ctx values (only key names) — a crash could leak operator data into log bus (cartBus.js:47-55). Verb argument values (only argsHash) — same reason; replay uses hash + log-stored response, not live args. LLM prompt content — sent to vendor; not stored in our logs; cost ledger records token counts, not text. LLM response content — same. Operator email / physical address / legal name — preamble carries user_id (opaque); preamble.py:207-209 heuristic rejects values that look like email or 'acct_'. OAuth tokens — encrypted in CredentialStore; logged only as trace-correlated audit row's verb outcome. Stripe payout details — surface not yet wired; would be subject to same discipline. PII categories per cart category — Blodgett pre/post-pass (verb_backings.py:62-128) decisions logged with kind + verdict only — never cleaned/blocked text.

The vendor-shaping floor. Following are NOT exposed on operator-facing surfaces. Vendor names — CLAUDE.md 2026-06-22 vendor-name lock; bake-in to LLM weights. Vendor cost-per-call — operators pay per-token-budget, not per-vendor; vendor cost is SRE-only. Vendor model strings (e.g. claude-sonnet-4-5-20251022) — lives only in _VERB_TO_MODEL tables in wire-call modules. Vendor URL paths — same, wire-call modules only. Vendor rate-limit window sizes — operator sees 'the marketplace is busy'; SRE sees <vendor>-rate-limit. Vendor-specific error codes — translated to capability errors before any operator-facing surface renders them.

The signal-not-noise floor. Following ARE measurable but deliberately NOT collected. Cursor position / keystroke timing in cart editor — not load-bearing; collection cost > observability value. Browser session details beyond user-agent header — privacy boundary; /api/me returns session shape, not browser fingerprint. Geo IP of every request — coarse-bucket country at most; never lat/long. Per-cart per-operator outcome cross-product — aggregates land in SYSTEM/sakura-recs; raw cross-product would re-identify operators below K-floor.

The sampling decision. Per LOAM §21.1 + cost-ledger ring buffer (§2.6) — we don't sample. Every wire-call records cost-ledger row; every cart event hits bus; every audit line lands in log. Volume-control mechanism is K-floor on COHORT plane reads (§6.4) plus retention policies (§8.5), not on write path. Rationale: telemetry honesty defeats sampling. A 1-in-100 sampled cost number is a story we tell ourselves; a real per-call number is the truth. We pay the storage cost.")

(chapter :number 11
         :title "§ORACLE — L1 Oracle Design (folded from meridian docs; reversal 2026-05-01-PM)"
         :section "ORACLE"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§ORACLE"))
         :prose "id LACUNA-MONITORING-L1-ORACLE-DESIGN-v0.1; status draft v0.1 with REVERSAL 2026-05-01-PM. Original chat-claude framing was 'Lacuna L0 SRE agent' — morning pass claimed misnamed under canonical taxonomy; Alfred clarified twice same day. AM: SRE orchestrator runs on operator's hardware (their Linux box, self-hosted Docker, or small managed Fly per-operator instance they run themselves) — so it's L0 semantically (operator-hardware tier), not L1. PM: Lacuna L0 is already designed — Qwen 2.5-3B trained on Linux stuff that's running now. SRE orchestrator IS Lacuna L0. Final canon: Lacuna runs L0/L1/L2, same depth as Sakura.

Implications. Chat-claude's 'Lacuna L0 SRE agent' framing was right all along. Morning's reconciliation was the drift. MRCL Router design, diagnostic chains, host-binding security, and Qwen-sizing material are Lacuna L0 content (Pillar 1 of lacuna design doc), not Lacuna Monitoring L1 content. Lacuna L0 (SRE orchestrator) and Lacuna Monitoring L1 (oracle) are two different things that share Qwen DNA but sit at different canonical tiers: Lacuna L0 LLM = active diagnosis on operator's hardware (reads syscalls, runs shell, traverses MRCL chains; Qwen 2.5-3B trained on Linux stuff); Lacuna Monitoring L1 LLM = passive observation on hosted infra (reads LMTP traces from lacunad, emits digests + anomaly callouts). MRCL Router content stays in source as historical record of morning's reconciliation. Canonical home for that material is lacuna/ai/llm/docs/lacuna-design-doc-v1.md § Pillar 1 — Lacuna L0 LLM: SRE orchestrator. Future pass should move implementation specifics over and leave pointer here.

What this doc still covers correctly: role of Lacuna Monitoring's L1 oracle (passive trace observation) and sizing question for that role specifically (whether 0.5B digest-only or larger reasoning is appropriate for trace digests). That role is genuinely L1 under canonical taxonomy — separate from SRE orchestrator at Lacuna L0.

Naming reconciliation (corrected — final). 'Lacuna L0 SRE agent' → Lacuna L0 LLM (SRE orchestrator on operator hardware); lives in lacuna/ repo (Pillar 1 of lacuna-design-doc-v1.md). 'Lacuna' (when meaning SRE agent) → Lacuna LLM (specifically Pillar 1: L0 SRE orchestrator). 'Lacuna' (when meaning trace observation) → Lacuna Monitoring (this product). Different product, different role.

Role. Oracle reads recent LMTP windows from lacunad, plus per-system context (process state, syscalls, error logs), and produces: digests (one-line ai_note annotations on LMTP records); anomaly callouts (surfaces patterns the operator should see); diagnostic chains (per chat-claude handoff: maps system call signatures to multi-step reasoning chains — filesystem, memory, network, scheduler, etc.). It DECIDES NOTHING. Echo (graceful failure) handles the case where oracle declines.

MRCL Router (chat-claude content, lifted as-is). Multi-Chain Reasoning Language routes patterns to diagnostic chains: stat/fstat errors → Filesystem Health Chain; mmap/brk growth → Memory Leak Detection Chain; connect/sendto timeout → Network Connectivity Chain; futex contention → Lock Contention & Scheduler Chain; others drafted in lacuna_qwen_orchestration.md, not in this repo yet. Chains live in YAML library (per chat-claude's prototype) so adding chains doesn't require model retraining. Model's job is to SELECT the chain and TRAVERSE its steps; library is deterministic ML in front of LLM.

Open: model + deployment decisions. Model size: today's canon says Qwen 2.5 0.5B at Q4_K_M (~0.6 GB resident, 16K context) — 'just digests log windows; doesn't reason multi-step.' Chat-claude proposes Qwen 1.5-1.5B quantized 4-bit (~2-3 GB at runtime, on Fly.io 2GB instance) — 'multi-step diagnostic reasoning needs more capacity than digesting.' Decision needed: digest-only (today's canon) or diagnostic reasoning (chat-claude). Pick one; size accordingly. Deployment topology: today's canon = per-machine (daemon runs everywhere; oracle is fixed-cost component owned by us; locality not specified). Chat-claude = centralized single Fly.io 2GB instance, ~$20/mo + DeepSeek API fallback for novel incidents (~$0.25-0.50/mo). Decision needed: centralized Fly vs per-operator local. May depend on whether diagnostic chains need cross-machine correlation (centralized wins) or not (local wins). DeepSeek API fallback: chat-claude proposes routing novel incidents (where local model is uncertain) to DeepSeek API at ~$0.07 per complex incident. Under canonical taxonomy this is Lacuna Monitoring L2. Today's canon says Lacuna Monitoring has no L2 — but canon was authored before fallback path was proposed. If chat-claude's recommendation lands, canon needs update: Lacuna Monitoring grows L2 tier specifically for novel-incident escalation. Decision needed: L2 tier vs oracle declines to Echo when uncertain.

Host binding (security). Chat-claude's proposal: enforce_host_binding(host_id_expected) — compute_host_id() as hash of hostname:mac:machine-id; if current != expected, refuse to operate, reset state on copy, sys.exit(127). Multi-signal binding (hostname + MAC + /etc/machine-id) so copied instance refuses to run with prior operator's state. Root access defeats it; casual copying doesn't. Security-domain concern (Tomas-veto) applying whenever L1 oracle accumulates per-operator state (incident corpus, fine-tuned weights). Adopt as default for any v0.2+ artifact that holds operator-derived state.

Fine-tune cadence. Chat-claude proposes: collect 1 month of incident data, then fine-tune Qwen 1.5-7B on postmortem corpus. Improves recurring-pattern accuracy. Phase 4+ deliverable, gated by L1 oracle shipping in any form, postmortem corpus actually accumulating, Kofi-veto on corpus. Open: parking until oracle's role is settled.")

(chapter :number 12
         :title "§SIZING — Deployment Sizing (Qwen 2.5 3B / nomic-embed / SigLIP; Mac Mini SKUs; memory math)"
         :section "SIZING"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§SIZING"))
         :prose "id DEPLOYMENT-SIZING-v0.1; chair Alfred (Architect), scribe Claude (PM), audience Kwame (SRE) for hardware procurement decision. Naming uses canonical L-tier taxonomy: 'Sakura LLM' means Sakura L1 LLM (vision) in production; L4/L5/L6 in cascade context maps to Sakura L1 LLM (text reasoner) and Sakura L2 LLM in prose; LAYER_* constants in cascade.py keep numeric forms (51 cascade tests depend on them). AI-judge is Lacuna Monitoring L1 oracle.

TL;DR. Biggest single model run locally is Qwen 2.5 3B. Not 7B. Not 70B. 3B handles every voice + register + light-reasoning task, passes persona-eval rubric, runs at 30+ t/s on Apple Silicon. Vision model is SigLIP ViT-L/16 + small heads — ~500 MB total; frozen. Do NOT farm vision to Google or any cloud vision API; defeats privacy + domain-fit + cost story. Embeddings are nomic-embed-text — 137 M params, ~270 MB. Lacuna Monitoring's AI-judge does not run yet; slot exists in dashboard; filling waits for Q3 when Lacuna LLM is trained; don't size for it. Mac Mini sweet spot: M4 with 24 GB unified memory ($799). Headroom for everything below + browser + dev tools without swap. 16 GB works but tight. 32+ GB is over-spec for next-week pipeline. Training is NOT local — LoRA fine-tunes go to Modal / RunPod for ~$10-30 a run. Mac Mini is inference + staging box, not training rig.

Per-model sizing lock-ins. L4 cascade + register-tuner: Qwen 2.5 3B Instruct, Q8 quantization. One model loaded once; LoRA adapter swapped per use (curator-3b vs register-tuner-base vs lacuna-3b when it ships). Why 3B not 0.5B: drops persona invariants under load (em-dash leaks, 'Great question' prefaces, cultural-attribution slips); fails at light multi-turn coherence (forgets operator's prior turn ~30% of time); can't reliably handle inference-shaped turns (compare-A-vs-B, 'should we...'). Why 3B not 7B: 7B is ~2x memory and ~2x latency for ~10% more capability on our domain; capability gain doesn't show up on eval rubric; 7B Q8 is ~7 GB — eats half the 16 GB Mini's RAM by itself; we're not running general-purpose chat. Why not Phi-3/Gemma/Llama 3: validated Qwen 2.5's voice with eval set; switching base means re-running whole calibration. L3 embeddings: nomic-embed-text v1.5. 137M params, ~270 MB. Local, no cloud round-trip, no per-call cost, no operator-data exfiltration, domain neutral. Sakura LLM (vision): SigLIP ViT-L/16 frozen + 3 head MLPs (trained per operator corpus). ~430 MB SigLIP backbone + ~3 MB total for three small MLP heads. Domain fit, privacy, cost, banded confidence vocabulary. Lacuna Monitoring L1 (oracle / AI-judge): DEFERRED. Dashboard's ai_note field exists in LMTP today; slot is empty. Filling requires small LLM. Sizing below assumes digest-only role (read window, emit one-line annotation); expansion to multi-step diagnostic reasoning would push size to ~1.5B + DeepSeek L2 fallback. Q3 target. Probably Qwen 2.5 0.5B is plenty; worst case reuse Qwen 3B (already loaded) with focused prompt; no extra RAM cost. Don't pre-load. Don't pre-buy RAM. Lacuna LLM (dialectical /argue): DEFERRED. Phase 4. Same base (Qwen 2.5 3B) with different LoRA adapter. No additional base model load — Ollama swaps adapters against resident base.

Memory math (worst-case). macOS + browser + IDE 5.0 GB; Ollama runtime 0.5 GB; Qwen 2.5 3B (Q8 base) 3.5 GB; LoRA adapters 0.1 GB; nomic-embed-text 0.3 GB; SigLIP ViT-L/16 + heads 0.5 GB; inference activation buffers 2.0 GB peak; lacunad daemon + dashboard tab 0.2 GB; Curator API + DB + frontend dev 1.0 GB. Total worst-case ~13 GB (~12 GB if Qwen at Q4). Hardware recommendation: Mac Mini M4 base, 32 GB unified, 512 GB SSD (~$999). 32 GB > 13 GB worst-case + room for 7B-model experiments. Token rate ~42 t/s on Qwen 3B Q8 is faster than typical operator typing. M4 chip 2-4 generations newer than M2 Pro. 5.0 x 5.0 x 2.0 inches, 0.7 kg. Fanless. Apple warranty. If 32 GB M4 isn't available, 24 GB M4 at $799 is solid drop-down. NOT: M1 Mini (capped at 16 GB, bandwidth-limited, 4 chip generations old); M4 Pro 24 GB ($1399, pays $600 for speed you won't notice on dev box); M4 Pro 48 GB (over-spec for pragmatic roadmap through Q3); Mac Mini M4 16 GB (tight; will swap; forces Q4 quant).

Roadmap (pragmatic). This week: Curator at v2.2.7 on dev:3000; cascade emits LMTP to lacunad. Mac Mini lands: migrate staging from laptop to Mini. Next week: Sakura LLM v0.1 trained off-box (Modal), deployed to Mini (+0.5 GB). 2 weeks: curator-3b LoRA shipped, replaces base Qwen for L4 (swap, no RAM change). 3 weeks: Lacuna LLM dialectical adapter shipped as separate Ollama tag (+0.1 GB LoRA only). Q3: AI-judge slot filled (likely Qwen 3B reuse, no new base) (+0 GB if reusing base). Q4+: multi-machine fabric, lacunad cluster, etc. — new sizing decision. Memory ceiling stays under 14 GB through Q3. 24 GB Mini is right-sized for entire pragmatic roadmap.")

(chapter :number 13
         :title "§PROBES — Probe registry (spec)"
         :section "PROBES"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§PROBES"))
         :prose "slug probe-registry; kind interface; version 1.0.0; owner meridian; status draft; extracted-from THE-PLAN.md Chapter 4 §4.9.

Purpose. Schema for freshness probes — scheduled checks that emit an event when the world (not a git commit) causes something to drift. Meridian owns the probe run-loop and registry format.

Scope. IN: .lacuna/freshness.yaml schema; probe execution semantics; alert paths; enumeration guidance. OUT: individual probe scripts (each lives in owning project's scripts/probes/); Meridian internal scheduler.

Definitions. Probe = script that exits 0 (green) or non-zero (fire) and prints a slat event to stdout. Freshness registry = .lacuna/freshness.yaml in each project. Cadence = interval at which a probe runs (e.g. 15m). Threshold = split between warn and alert levels.

Registry file. Example: id shop-inventory-fresh, probe ./scripts/probes/shop-inventory-age.sh, interval 15m, threshold warn {rows-older-than 6h, percent 5} alert {rows-older-than 24h, percent 1}, on-warn notify:sre-channel, on-alert [notify:sre-channel, open-issue:in-stock-freshness], ttl 90d. Fields: id (string, unique per repo); probe (path, relative path to check script); interval (duration — 15m, 1h, 24h, etc.); threshold (mapping — domain-specific keys, warn and alert levels); on-warn (string or list, alert path); on-alert (string or list, alert path); ttl (duration — how long probe can go without green tick before it opens 'probe stale' issue).

Probe execution. Where probes run: freshness-probes.yml (GitHub Actions cron) + optionally an edge worker for sub-minute cadence. Edge worker POSTs status back to repo Pages endpoint that freshness-probes.yml reads on next run. Every probe MUST emit slat probe-tick record on completion (green or fire) to Meridian's log directory: (probe-tick :probe 'shop-inventory-fresh' :ok #t :ts '2026-07-09T22:00:00Z' :rows-older-than-6h-pct 2.1). See SLAT-1.0.SPEC.md §4.1 for canonical probe-tick shape (SLAT record taxonomy) and §5.1 for .slatl framing.

Alert paths. Two destinations only: notify:<channel> — a message, no page, weekly digest to SRE lead; page:sre-oncall — real page, reserved for probes where human must act within an hour. Between them: open-issue:<template> — creates GitHub issue from template, assigned by CODEOWNERS. This is where most alerts belong: durable, discussable, closeable. Slack drops on floor. Issues do not. There is no global 'page for everything' — every probe declares its own escalation.

First-cut enumeration. shop-inventory-fresh, shop-price-fresh, easypost-signup-healthy, shippo-signup-healthy, taxjar-signup-healthy, cloudinary-signup-healthy, vies-signup-healthy, gsc-signup-healthy, bing-signup-healthy, cart-run-telemetry-arriving, marketplace-heartbeat-* (per configured marketplace), sakura-4b-checkpoint-load, loam-plane-health, cortex-ambient-context-fresh.

Compatibility and versioning. Additive: new probe fields, new alert paths. Breaking: changing file location, changing probe-tick shape.")

(chapter :number 14
         :title "§ALERTS — Alert routing (spec)"
         :section "ALERTS"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§ALERTS"))
         :prose "slug alert-routing; kind interface; version 1.0.0; owner meridian; status draft; extracted-from THE-PLAN.md Chapter 4 §4.9.

Purpose. Three alert paths Meridian supports and rules for which fires produce which path. No pager fatigue; no dropped alerts.

Scope. IN: three alert paths (notify, page, open-issue); rules deciding which fires produce which path; retry + escalation semantics. OUT: specific pager service (config, not a spec); individual issue templates (live under .github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/).

Definitions. Notify = message to a channel, no page, aggregated into weekly digest. Page = real page, wakes human, reserved for 'must act within one hour' tier. Open-issue = creates GitHub issue from named template, assigned by CODEOWNERS. Fire = probe or trigger emitting non-green state that MAY produce an alert.

The three paths. notify:<channel> — latency seconds, human action expected read at leisure, aggregation weekly digest to SRE lead. page:sre-oncall — latency seconds, act within 1 h, no aggregation (every page individual). open-issue:<template> — latency minutes, discuss/close eventually, no aggregation (issues durable).

Which fires go to which path. notify — informational fires ('Marketplace X throttling us but under quota'). page — action-within-an-hour fires ('sakura-4b checkpoint fails to load', 'production endpoint returning 5xx > 5%'). open-issue — everything else. Durable, discussable, closeable. Rule: every probe and trigger declares own alert path in .lacuna/freshness.yaml or .lacuna/triggers.yaml. No global 'page for everything' — that way lies alert fatigue.

Compound paths. Single fire MAY produce multiple paths. Example: on-alert [notify:sre-channel, open-issue:in-stock-freshness]. Paths run in listed order. If any path throws error, remaining paths still execute — routing is best-effort per-destination.

Retries. Meridian retries page up to 3 times, 30-second backoff. notify retries once. open-issue retries up to 5 times, exponential backoff — issue creation MUST NOT be lost.

Escalation. If a page is not acknowledged within 15 minutes, Meridian escalates to second channel (declared per-probe or per-project). No further escalation past that layer — design assumption is small team.

Compatibility and versioning. Additive: new templates, new channels. Breaking: removing a path, changing retry semantics.")

(chapter :number 15
         :title "§GAPS — Telemetry gaps (SRE attestation 2026-07-02)"
         :section "GAPS"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§GAPS"))
         :prose "Marcus's SRE attestation (docs/SRE-ATTESTATION-2026-07-02.md, filed 2026-07-02) identified five material gaps between this document's specifications and running system's actual wiring as of that date. Each with blocker and living marker.

Gaps table. (1) Percentile naming drift — spec says p90 (multiple metric allow-list entries); reality p95 (all emitted telemetry). Unblocks: standardize on p95 across allow-list and this doc. LIVING:TODO(2026-07-06). (2) Latency capture unwired — spec says per-verb, per-cart, per-wire-call latency percentiles are metric-allowed; reality no emit sites, allow-list only. Unblocks: wire latency capture at cart host. LIVING:TODO(2026-07-06). Note: subsequent 2026-07 wave landed sre/latency_ring.py (§4.2 documents it), closing part of this gap. (3) Event spine not fed by prod — spec says event_spine.py:emit() fed by all cart runs; reality only hit_rate.py + migration script call it. Unblocks: wire prod cart host → event spine. LIVING:TODO(2026-07-06). (4) Alerting pipeline dark — spec says alert logic in lacuna_14b.py:180-253 + lacuna_sre/alerting.py; reality logic exists but no daemon/poller instantiates or runs it at runtime. Unblocks: attach daemon/poller; wire cost-cap webhook as template. LIVING:TODO(2026-07-06). (5) loam-health.sh absent — spec says referenced as tools/ utility in §6; reality does not exist. RESOLVED 2026-07-03: confirmed at tools/loam-health.sh per HEAD d4f5a8a4.

Percentile naming (p90 vs p95). Emitted telemetry uniformly reports p95 latencies. This document and metric allow-list should be standardized to match.

Latency percentile capture. Per-verb, per-cart, per-wire-call latency percentile metrics whitelisted in allow-list (§9) but have no corresponding emit sites in cart host. Needs emit-site wiring at cart host. Partial closure via sre/latency_ring.py.

Event spine not fed by prod. event_spine.py:emit() exists but called only from hit_rate.py and data-migration script. Production cart host runs do not feed event spine. Needs wire cart host → event spine.

Alerting pipeline dark. Alert logic implemented in lacuna_14b.py:180-253 and lacuna_sre/alerting.py but has no runtime daemon or poller attached. Only live alert in production is the cost-cap webhook. Needs daemon/poller attachment.")

(chapter :number 16
         :title "§SLAT — Telemetry on the SLAT wire"
         :section "SLAT"
         :dialect "sakura"
         :audience "engineer"
         :training-eligible #f
         :confidentiality "internal"
         :provenance ((:source-path "/Users/alfred/code/sakura-scheme/docs/engineering/TELEMETRY-MEDIAN-1.0.ENG.md") (:source-anchor "§SLAT"))
         :prose "Cross-refs: SLAT-1.0.SPEC.md, LOAM-1.0.ENG.md §SLAT, CORTEX-1.0.ENG.md §SLAT. Task #62 landed the ENG-tree surface pass; this section threads SLAT through cart lifecycle events, cost ledger, wire-call observability, and probe surface. Additive to §1-§11 and §PROBES + §ALERTS folded sections; no deletes. Marcus reviews this section.

Doctrine. Telemetry records what happens. Every record has a time, subject, kind, payload. SLAT is the wire form. Load-bearing property: every record produced by telemetry pipeline can be read by any downstream consumer with the same reader, without a translator. Cross-binding stability (SLAT §9.4) is what makes cross-service telemetry composable. Cart-side JS emits event slat; Python-side Loam ingest reads same bytes; SRE dashboard's Python-side aggregator sees same value; operator's front-end reads it back on the way to render. Same reader, four steps.

cartBus events as event slats. §1.1 taxonomy enumerates the events; each becomes an event slat (SLAT §4.1 row 2): (event :ts inst :kind 'cart.gate.enter' :cart-id 'etsy-listing-draft :cart-tier 'pink :operator 'operator/op-042' :trace-id 'tr-a4f9c2' :duration-ms 12). Taxonomy names (cart.gate.enter, cart.step.enter, cart.step.done, cart.error, cart.done) are :kind values. Downstream projections match on :kind lexically. Taxonomy is stable; adding a kind is additive per §1.2 sequence + timestamp guarantees.

Cost row schema as record slats. §2.2 names persisted shape. In SLAT terms it is a record slat with reserved keys: (record :kind 'cost-row :ts inst :vendor 'anthropic :verb 'sakura/reason :operator 'operator/op-042' :cart-id 'etsy-listing-draft :trace-id 'tr-a4f9c2' :input-tokens 1240 :output-tokens 380 :cost-cents 12.4M :cache-hit #t). :cost-cents uses bigdecimal (SLAT §3.3). Money is not a vector. Two identical cost rows produce identical canonical bytes (SLAT §6.1) — cost-ledger deduplicator uses content-id (SLAT §5.4) as primary key.

Loam plane rows are slats. §2.4 describes plane. In wire form, plane is a .slatl stream (SLAT §5.1) of the cost-row slats above. LOAM §SLAT.2 walks projection-authoring pattern; every projection matches on head + keywords. §6.2 SYSTEM plane row table is one row per event, one line per row. Auto-assembly registry (SLAT §7) rehydrates each row to native SystemRow object when consumer registers a builder.

Wire-call counters + latency as event slats. §4.1 maintains counters keyed on (verb, tier, operator). Every increment produces event slat: (event :ts inst :kind 'wire.call.done' :verb 'etsy/listing-update :vendor 'etsy :operator 'operator/op-042' :latency-ms 340 :status 'ok :size-in-bytes 1240 :size-out-bytes 380). §4.2 latency capture shows Python code; every capture emits one slat. §4.3 rate-limit envelope produces rate-limit record slat matching LACUNA-INTEGRATION §SLAT.5 exactly — one shape across two docs.

Probe-tick canonical form. §PROBES §7.5 shows shape; SLAT §4.1 makes it the probe-tick registry row. Full shape: (probe-tick :probe 'shop-inventory-fresh' :ok #t :ts inst :duration-ms 45 :context (:rows-older-than-6h-pct 2.1M)). Probe-ticks land on ~/.lacuna/meridian/probe-ticks.slatl. Loam ingest computes per-probe green/fire rates; SRE dashboard reads same slatl on way to rendering probe grid.

Cross-binding stability. §2.3 tier→rollup translation runs in Python. §4.2 latency capture pattern runs in JS on cart side. §7 SRE dashboards reads both from Loam. Cross-binding contract (SLAT §9.4) means every consumer parses same bytes to same value. This is what closes observability spine. Without it, tier translation lives in Python, cart latency lives in JS, dashboards read either and hope for best. With SLAT canonical form, all three see same records.

Backward compat. Old telemetry paths that emit JSON continue to work — ingest tries SLAT first, JSON second (SLAT §10.4 migration timeline). Deprecation warning fires on JSON reads so migration completes. tools/loam-health.sh diagnostic (§GAPS above) will emit slat probe-ticks once authored — new tooling ships SLAT-native.

Cross-references. SLAT primitives — SLAT §3. event/record/probe-tick registry rows — SLAT §4.1. Line-delimited .slatl framing — SLAT §5.1. Content-id + Merkle attestation — SLAT §5.4, §6.7. Cross-binding stability — SLAT §9.4. Migration timeline — SLAT §10.4. Loam ingest + projections — LOAM §SLAT. Cortex event bus — CORTEX §SLAT.4. Vendor rate-limit envelope — LACUNA-INTEGRATION §SLAT.5.")

